      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Nigerian society is a melting pot of ethnic tensions, primarily between the Hausa-Fulani, Yoruba, and Igbo groups. The Hausa-Fulani, who are predominantly Muslim, often dominate the political and economic spheres, leading to resentment among the Yoruba and Igbo, who are mostly Christian and animist. The Yoruba, in particular, have a history of rivalry with the Hausa-Fulani, which sometimes erupts into violent clashes. The Igbo, meanwhile, have faced brutal oppression during the Biafra War and harbor deep-seated mistrust towards the Hausa-Fulani. These ethnic tensions can lead to friction in daily interactions, with each group vying for control and influence.",
